We finally made it to Puerto 511 and were not disappointed. We had reservation at 6 pm and there is free street parking nearby. Every one of the 5 savory courses were delicious, beautiful to the eyes and full of contrasting textures and favors. I have shellfish allergy, which the chef kindly accommodated without advance notice. The space is comfortable and the service was attentive. The tamal was so delicious that I could eat another 5-6 easily. My favorite was the Thai tiradito, a ceviche with the most yummy lime-coconut milk dressing. A spoon was knowingly provided so that the child in me did not have to pick up the bowl to drink every delicious drop. We are looking forward to going back and recommending this lovely place to our friends.

Went to this place last night, and I think it might be the best meal I have ever had in Baltimore. The inside is nice and cozy. Be aware, it is not a big space, maybe 20 or 30 seats tops, so if you're planning on going on a weekend, I wouldn't take a chance of just walking in. The menu is also pre-fixed on Friday and Saturday, but honestly, after my experience, I would eat whatever Chef Alarcon cooks me. I don't care. It's BYOB, so be cognizant of that as well.  The service was very good. With a restaurant that small, they really don't have a dedicated server. The chef pretty much brought every plate directly to us, which was really nice.  The "mesero" brought out some fried platanos to the table as we were getting settled, and they were great. I used to eat them when I was young, but they were just chips from a bag, and these blew my childhood memories out of the water.  We had two appetizers. My girlfriend had the Ceviche Mixto Arocotado and loved it, and I had the Anticucho De Corazon, and it was amazing. The meat had a wonderful smoky taste that immediately made me miss having a backyard to grill food, and even the potato was grilled. The sauce was spicy and delicious. This was my first experience with Peruvian corn, and it was really great as well. A little more interesting than your run of the mill yellow corn.  We shared the Chaufa as an entree, and the quality and flavors were absolutely amazing. I don't think I've had a meal that was overall this good in years. You can definitely tell that the chef cares deeply about what comes out of his kitchen, and he has a personal stake in every dish that he makes. I've had some good dishes at other restaurants, but I loved everything Chef Alarcon put on our plates. I will 100% be back, hopefully to try the weekend fixed menu. Thank you very much Puerto 511.

I ordered the ceviche mixto and loved it. It had incredible flavors and ingredients. My boyfriend ordered the chaufa which was delicious. He also ordered the hearts which I didn't try but he really liked. The staff was very attentive. Dining room is small but cozy.

Fernandini y que prepare entrada, segundo y postre para cuatro personas con veinte luquitas…dan ganas de regresar y meterle un frentazo por pendejo!!!!

perfect the service was informative and warm I felt like I was in their kitchen at their home treated like a guest (as at most homes they are not in a rush but neither was I) but for my the real test of a restaurant is food ceviche is perfect tamales to die for lamb chops ... th eonly complaint I have is that I didn't get fifty the homemade dulce de leche is sublime with the peruvian toast
The one and only....try it!

I love trying Peruvian restaurants in the MD area. This spot is a must... I haven't had a meal like this in years. The "causa rellena" and "tiradito" were amazing, and the "arroz con mariscos" was beyond compare (loved the "rocoto" sauce that came with the entree). I'd love to see the menu expanding some more, however the few dishes they do, are simply quality, far from others in the area. Outstanding taste! Will return soon for more.

The place is has a hole-in-the-wall feel, with high prices. Small and intimate dining area, great for dates. Small menu makes deciding what to order easy. Would recommend making reservations in advance, due to limited seating. BYOB, with a fee. Plantain chips in place of bread. The dipping sauce was bland. The ceviche is extraordinary, as was the tamale appetizer. We ordered the wok fried rice/ pallea dish which was pretty, but slightly over done. Prices are high; esp for the small portion sizes. The executive chef serves as the waiter as well and serves you directly. (Service is slower)  Would recommend for ceviche.

This place is a find!  It is a small restaurant (5 tables) with a chef (the owner), sous chef and waitress (the chef's wife).  Everything is cooked to order.  I went with a group of 5 and we all tried different appetizers and entrees.  Everything was incredible.  They have 3 different kinds of ceviche.  We tried 2 and they were not only delicious but very fresh.  It is also BYOB which we loved.  I highly recommend this restaurant.
